<sn><md>#### Stationary sources:

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-2
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/air-quality-dgrm7.1.png)
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-5
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/air-quality-dgrm7.png)
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-5
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/air-quality-dgrm8.png)
:::
:::


Stationary sources are those that have a `relatively fixed location`. These include `point` sources, `fugitive` sources and `area` sources.

* **a) Point sources:** Point sources are stationary sources that `emit pollutants from one or more controllable sites` such as smokestacks of power plants at industrial sites.
* **b) Fugitive sources:** Fugitive sources `generate air pollutants from open areas` exposed to wind processes such as dirt roads, construction sites, farmlands and surface mines etc.
* **c) Area sources:** Area sources are locations `having several sources from which air pollutants are emitted`. For example, agricultural areas sprayed with herbicides and pesticides.

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Mobile sources:

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-8
Mobile sources are emitters of air pollutants that `move from place to place while yielding emissions`. These include automobiles, trucks, buses, ships, aircraft and trains.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-4
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/air-quality-dgrm5.png)
:::
:::




</md></sn><sn><md>#### Natural &amp; Indoor Sources

Besides, there are natural sources of air pollutants.

![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/air-quality-dgrm3.png)

* **Natural Sources:** `Volcanoes discharge ash`, `acid mist` and $\text{H}_2\text{S}$.`Natural forest fires` create clouds of smoke. `Trees and bushes` emit millions of tons of volatile organic compounds (terpenes and propenes), pollen, spores, viruses, bacteria in the air and cause widespread suffering from allergies and airborne infections.
* **Indoor Sources:** Pollutants are also found indoor that infiltrate from air outside and from various chemicals used in buildings.

Both inside and outside pollutants create a high risk for human health.
</md></sn><sn><md>The quality of air depends on **three factors**:

1. The amount of pollutants.
2. The rate at which they are released into the atmosphere.
3. How long they are trapped in an area.

---

Air quality is degraded by the day to day emissions from different air pollution sources. These include:

* **Stationary sources:** such as power plants, manufacturing facilities, smelters, motor machines and burning wood and coal.
* **Mobile sources:** such as trucks, buses, planes and cars.
* **Natural sources:** such as volcanic eruptions and windstorm dust.

The pollutants from these sources are released into the air which can affect the health of humans, animals and our environment.</md></sn>